# Memory Leaking with `Box::leak` in Rust

## Basic Example

```rust
fn leak_string() -> &'static str {
    let s = String::from("Hello, leaked world!");
    Box::leak(s.into_boxed_str())
}

fn main() {
    let leaked: &'static str = leak_string();
    println!("{}", leaked);
    // Memory is never freed, but reference is valid for program lifetime
}
```

## Comprehensive Examples

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::sync::OnceLock;

// ============================================================
// 1. GLOBAL CONFIGURATION (most common legitimate use case)
// ============================================================

/// Config loaded once at startup, needed for entire program lifetime.
/// Using Box::leak avoids needing a Mutex<Option<Config>> or OnceLock overhead
/// when the data is truly write-once.
#[derive(Debug)]
struct AppConfig {
    database_url: String,
    max_connections: u32,
    feature_flags: HashMap<String, bool>,
}

static CONFIG: OnceLock<&'static AppConfig> = OnceLock::new();

fn initialize_config(db_url: &str) -> &'static AppConfig {
    CONFIG.get_or_init(|| {
        let config = AppConfig {
            database_url: db_url.to_string(),
            max_connections: 10,
            feature_flags: {
                let mut map = HashMap::new();
                map.insert("dark_mode".to_string(), true);
                map.insert("beta_features".to_string(), false);
                map
            },
        };
        // Leak the Box, promoting heap allocation to 'static lifetime
        Box::leak(Box::new(config))
    })
}

fn get_config() -> &'static AppConfig {
    CONFIG.get().expect("Config not initialized")
}

// ============================================================
// 2. FFI - Passing ownership to C code
// ============================================================

/// When C code takes ownership of memory and will free it via its own
/// mechanisms, we must leak from Rust's perspective.
